<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0115</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Draft Deregulation Bill: submission from the Ramblers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Ramblers – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Evidence submitted by the Ramblers on clauses 12–18 and Schedule 6 of the draft Bill</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clauses 12 to 18 and Schedule 6 appear in the draft Deregulation Bill, as the direct result of the work of the Natural England Stakeholder Working Group (SWG).  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The recommendations represent a consensus view of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> across the rights of way sector (landowners and land managers, local authorities and rights of way user groups).  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The implementation of the recommendations will require a mixture of primary and secondary legislation as well as guidance. Because of the complex nature of the legislation in question the clauses still require further work by Parliamentary draftsmen to ensure that they properly follow the intentions of the SWG.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Ramblers and the other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> represented on the Group continue to work with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Natural England to ensure that the clauses have their desired effect.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The provisions in the present Bill are part of a package, and if some parts were introduced, and others dropped, then there is a strong risk that the consensus would be lost.  Any additional measures recommended by the Joint Committee in the light of its deliberations would not necessarily carry cross-sector support.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The Ramblers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Ramblers is a charity which seeks (among other things) to promote walking, both as a recreation and as the most sustainable form of transport. We also seek to promote the health, recreation and environmental benefits of walking, especially by protecting and extending the network of public paths and access in town and countryside, through lobbying, campaigning and voluntary practical work, and, since April 2012, through our partnership with Macmillan Cancer Support, in which we run the Walking for Health project, delivering strategic guidance for the England-wide health walks programme and providing schemes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such support and free resources as training, insurance, and national promotion. (The local schemes are run by a variety of organisations including councils, the NHS, charities and voluntary groups.) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition to supporting Walking for Health walks, we organise 45,000 led walks per year. 12,000 volunteers lead the walks; about 300,000 people take part in them. We have been organising these led walks since our formation in 1935.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are submitting this statement to the Joint Committee to emphasise our support for the work and recommendations of the Natural England Stakeholder Working Group, and our desire to see the rights of way clauses included in the present Bill. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The need for amending legislation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are in no doubt that Parliamentary time should be afforded to reforming rights of way legislation because the present system is not operating with the speed and efficiency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">needed to ensure that all rights of way are properly recorded on definitive maps</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by the “cut-off date” introduced by the Countryside and Right of Way Act 2000</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  It is in the public interest that rights of way should be effectively managed, by which we mean administered, recorded, maintained and kept free from obstruction,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not least</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> because of the well documented health and economic benefits which accrue from their existence. By ‘health benefits’, we refer to, for example, the fact that brisk walking improves circulation and the performance of the heart and lungs.  Walking can lower blood-pressure; it can reduce risk of stroke, and of heart disease, the UK’s biggest killer. It can improve control of blood sugar in type-two diabetes; it has an important role in cardiac rehabilitation.  And walking promotes mental health and well-being, and improves self-perception and self-esteem and mood; it has the potential to be as effective as anti depressants or psychotherapy in treating depression.   Widespread take-up could massively lighten the economic burden caused by physical inactivity (in 2009 each Primary Care Trust spent an average of £5m on dealing with its consequences).  By  ‘economic benefits’, we mean, for example, the 6.14 billion pounds which walkers spend annually in the English countryside, the income in excess of 2 billion pounds which they generate, and the 245,000 full-time jobs which they support.  Walking tourism in rural and coastal Wales is estimated to contribute over £550million to the economy.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The clauses in the present Bill derive directly from the work of the ‘Natural England Stakeholder Working Group on Unrecorded Public Rights of Way’.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The genesis of the Group, its work and its recommendations are set out in detail in the document ‘Stepping Forward’, which can be viewed on the Natural England website</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The recommendations, first made to Government in 2010, represent a consensus reached by representatives of all sectors with an interest in rights of way (landowners and land managers, users (including the Ramblers) and local authorities.  It is a package of measures which must be taken as a whole: to take particular recommendations in isolation, or to introduce additional measures on which there is no agreement, will be to risk the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">break up</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the consensus.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The recommendations of the Group are wide-ranging and complex and will need to be introduced by means of primary and secondary legislation and guidance.  Because of the need to amend existing primary legislation there is no option but to opt for new primary legislation, and the SWG will continue to work with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Natural England on these reforms both during the passage of the present Bill through Parliament, and beyond.  The legislation is complex and work continues on the drafting of individual clauses and the Schedule to ensure that it properly represents the views of the SWG.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The provisions operate to deregulate at a number of levels, for example:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause 12 limits the scope for deletion orders and so should lower the number of deletion applications.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause 14 safeguards the position of landowners who rely on unrecorded rights of way to reach their properties and so should avoid the need for any action by such landowners to protect their access.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause 16, by empowering the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">authorisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of gates on byways, will make the recognition of such ways less contentious.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause 18 gives effect to Schedule 6 which contains the changes necessary to bring about the simplification of the procedures for ascertaining rights of way (i.e. adding paths to the definitive map, and so </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recognising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> them as rights of way).  So for example, it introduces, amongst other measures, the principle of an issue being sent to the Secretary of State for consideration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> only once (not possibly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> twice as is the case now), allows a local authority to dismiss irrelevant objections to an order, and for the re-alignment of claimed paths (so making them less contentious).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Ramblers commends the inclusion of the rights of way clauses in the draft Deregulation Bill: it is essential that reforms are introduced as soon as possible because of the cut-off date.  In the mean time, the Ramblers will continue to work with the SWG and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on the wider SWG recommendations to ensure improvements in the administration and management of public rights of way.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Ramblers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The legal record of public rights of way held by each surveying authority in England and Wales</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Subject to certain exceptions, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he ‘cut-off date’ of 1 January 2026, introduced by the Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000, will extinguish any pre-1949 public rights which have not been recorded on definitive maps by that time.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/access/rightsofway/unrecorded/default.aspx"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/access/rightsofway/unrecorded/default.aspx</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>